|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   Ok, let's move on to tonight topic:  Stayman and Transfers still leave us with some gaps in our arsenal.

Specifically we need a way to handle very strong responding hands that don't have a long suit and putting a little more "precision" into our invitations to 3NT.

If Responder has a really strong balanced hand and we don't find a fit via Stayman, or if Responder doesn't have a 4-card Major, then the quantitative 4NT is the normal weapon of choice.

The next thing I'm going to show you is something I developed about 38 years ago.

Playing 4-suit transfers puts a lot of emphasis on Stayman for invitational sequences, and because Stayman does give opps a fair amount of information about the distribution of your hands and primarily is aimed at finding 4-4 Major suit fits, sometimes to no good effect, we wanted to find a better way.

I also really disliked the quantitative 4NT because it sometimes meant playing in 4NT rather than 3NT and going off because the cards were distributed unkindly.

You will have noticed from the outline of the scheme I gave you last week that the 1NT - 2@D sequence shows EITHER a transfer to @HHearts@H OR a invitational+ hand.

If Opener completes the transfer to 2@H and Responder then bids ANYTHING other than 2@S, this confirms they have a 5+-card heart suit and is totally natural, just like in any normal transfer scheme.  So 
^c@2
1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 3@C  ^hstill shows a Heart/Club 2-suited hand and is game-forcing

1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 3NT  ^hstill shows a game-going semi-balanced hand with 5-card Hearts 

1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 3@S  ^hshows a game-forcing Major 2-suiter with longer Hearts   (note 3@S not 2@s).
|
