cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  The advantage of using this method is that it can ALSO be used with hands which would otherwise bid a quantitative 1NT - 4NT, but can investigate whether Opener is minimum or maximum in a FORCING way and still play in 2NT when Responder ONLY has an invitation to 3NT, and in 3NT if Responder is very strong but we don't quite have enough for 6NT.

So 1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 2@S - 2NT(MINIMUM), Responder can pass if them have a hand that was only worth a strong invitation, or bid on if them have a hand that was exploring for slam.

The Stayman sequence  1NT - 2@C - 2x - 2NT  is still available for invitational hands.

The difference between the 2 sequences is that the Stayman sequence is used where the implication is that responder only wants to be in game only if Opener is MAXIMUM, and the 2-way 2@D sequence is used where responder wants to be in game if Opener is BETTER THAN MINIMUM.

Suppose we're vulnerable and so 1NT shows 13-15 points.

Partner opens 1NT and we've a balanced 10-count with no redeeming features.

Now we use the Stayman sequence, because we only want to be in game if Opener has a nice 15-count.

If, on the other hand, we have an 11-count rather than a 10-count, we really can't afford not to be in game if Opener has anything better than a rock-bottom minimum, so now we use the 2-way 2@D sequence, and the bidding goes  1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 2@S   (the 2@s cancels the transfer and shows the invitational hand).

Opener bids 2NT with a minimum, 3NT with a maximum 3343 or 3334 with a 4-card minor suit (NOT with 5332 shape), or bids 4+-card suits "upwards" at the 3-level if they are BETTER than MINIMUM.

If Opener bids 2NT to show a minimum, then responder can continue either by bidding 3NT or by themselves bidding 4-card suits upwards at the 3-level.

If Responder does this then they are showing a very strong hand.|
