With 5+ card Clubs, and 4-card @H, we'd be bidding  1NT - 2@S - 3@C - 3@H  but like I said, better to agree the trump suit explicitly if you can.

The time you might do it IMPLICITLY is in a different situation when you could only agree it explicitly at game level and so risk it being misinterpreted as a sign-off.

If responder does anything OTHER than bid 2@S over  1NT - 2@D - 2@H,  then this confirms the transfer to hearts and carries the normal meaning it would have done anyway.

Thus  1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 2NT  is a semi-balanced invitation with a 5-card heart suit, and  1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 3@C   shows a game-forcing Heart Club 2-suiter. 

The bid "lost" by this method is one used to show a game-forcing 2-suiter with 4-card spades and 5-card or longer Hearts.

The 2@S rebid would be forcing in any transfer system, so the sequence  1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 3@S  is used with a hand of that type.

Similarly the sequence 

^c1NT - 2@C - 2@D - 3@H   could be used with a hand that was only worth an invitation, and

^c1NT - 2@C - 2@D - 2@H   for a weak hand of this shape.

So we do potentially lose one round of bidding when Responder has a slam-going hand Major 2-suiter with longer Hearts (because Responder has to rebid 3@S rather than 2@S), but what we GAIN from the 2-way 2@D vastly outweighs that.

