fp|t-title|at|The  1NT - 2@d         Super Accept  Re-visited|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  You may remember that earlier I said that if Opener wants to "super-accept" over a  1NT - 2@D  sequence, we use the "worthless-doubleton" method rather than cue-bidding our cheapest Ace.

This is very important to remember and there's a very good reason why: Over a sequence like 1NT - 2@H, we KNOW Responder has at least a 5-card Spade suit, but if we are using the  2-way 2@D,  that is not necessarily true.

If we super-accept over  1NT - 2@D,  Responder may not have Hearts at all and showing a worthless doubleton if we have one helps to ensure that we do not get into "silly" 3NT contracts where we have xx opposite something like Jxx when there may be a better alternative on offer.

Suppose you hold   @Sxx  @HQJ98  @DAQxx  @cAQx   ...and partner bids  2@D  over your Vulnerable 1NT Opening.

You super-accept with  3@D  (the suit below the doubleton, skipping 'agreed' trumps)  rather than  2@H.

If Responder has 5+ Hearts then you sail away to your Heart contract at whatever level Responder dictates.

Suppose, Responder has a holding like this:   @S10x  @HAKx  @Dxxx  @CKJ109x

Over Opener's  3@d (showing a @s dbltn) super-accept, Responder knows that 3NT is not a safe resting spot and that playing 4@H in a Moysian fit is hugely safer.

If Opener had cue-bid their cheapest Ace instead of showing a worthless doubleton, we would be none the wiser and would probably end up in a hopeless 3NT.

This is the reason why we break the transfers differently over  1NT - 2@D   compared to    1NT - 2@H.
|
