cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  So over  1NT - 2@H,  if we super-accept the trannsfer to Spades, we're ALWAYS going to end up playing this hand in Spades, but the same is NOT true over  1NT - 2@D  if the 2@D bid is 2-way.

I am now going to briefly cover how we continue when Opener super-accepts Hearts, but Responder doesn't have a 5-card or even a 4-card Heart suit.

Responders action will always depend on  
^c(1)   The strength and distribution of their own hand and
^c(2)   Exactly HOW Opener breaks the transfer.

As I said before, to break the transfer to 2@H, Opener will be   maximum,  have decent controls  and  GOOD 4-card @H support (at least Hxxx).

They will bid the suit BELOW a worthless doubleton if they have one, bid 2NT with a 4432 shape hand that doesn't have a worthless doubleton, or 3@H with a 3433 shape hand.

So how Responder proceeds depends on which is these methods Opener choose and how that marries up with Responder's strength and distribution.

Mainly, Responder takes some action that doesn't involve supporting Hearts.

This will often involve merely bidding 3NT if they had an invitational strength hand unless Opener's bid has pinpointed a worthless-doubleton that matches a weakness in Responder's hand.

Similarly if they had an invitational strength hand WITH 5-card or even 4-card Hearts, they'll just bid game in Hearts.

If Responder starts bidding OTHER suits, then they're either looking for a game other than 3NT because we have a matching weakness in one suit, or they're looking for a slam.
