at|So when do we use  Stayman  and when the  2-way 2@D  given we have a balanced hand?  Suppose Opener has opened a  13-15  1NT and we are balanced with an HCP of
^c@2
0 - 9   ^e^*b Pass^*n   since we can't possibly get to game.

10      ^e^*b Stayman^*n   because we only want to be in game opposite a maximum.

11      ^e^*b 2-way 2@D^*n   because we want to be in game unless Opener is minimum.

12 - 14 ^e^*b 3NT^*n   or use  ^*bStayman^*n  to find a fit, because we want to be in game whatever Opener has.
^f@2We might use the  ^*b2-way 2@D^*n  if we have a 4-4 in the Minors and weak doubleton in a Major 
(OR  perhaps if we're 4144 or similar)   in case  5@C or 5@D  might be better than 3NT.
^c@2
15+, ^e^*b 2-w@2ay 2@D^*n   We tend to use the  ^*b2-way 2@D^*n  because it's better at finding the Minor-suit fits as well as Major-suit fits and we're starting to think in terms of a slam.
^b@2

So as you can see there's no simple rule as to whether you use  Stayman  or the  2-way 2@D.

It chops and changes according to Responder's exact strength relative to the 1NT Opening, and their distribution 
